column4: Beaver Tail Light, Dutch Island, Providence

column3: The wind Easterly commenced  discharging took the deckload of down to the rails wrote letter home
The wind Easterly and rainy. work a little while and stoped on account of the rain
The wind North West finished deckload and let the hold full out by the Job
The wind Westerly laid at the wharf
The wind W. S. W. the crew loafing while the Lumber was being taken out
The wind Southerly and Westerly laying to the wharf having the Lumber taken out
The wind South West got unloaded at 8 oclock AM  took tugboat out from the wharf and towed in the River and made sail and beat down to Dutch Island and anchored at 9 p.m. Bound to New York
The wind South West laid at anchor in Duck Island Harbor work on vessel.

The wind South West in forenoon and hauled around to the North West. at night. Got under way at dark and went out moderate untill 12 oclock at night and the wind beginning to breeze up to the Eastward
The wind Easterly passed the Little Gull at 11:30 am Falkner's Island at 3 P.M. and and anchored Smith town bay 10 at p.m. thick with fog.
column4: Little Gull Island, Falkner's Island, Smith Town Bay

column3: Calm in the morning At 7 oclock a very moderate wind to the North got underway at 8 oclock Calm. and at 12. the wind breezing up South West. beat up the Sound.

The wind South. W. abrest of Execution Rock at day light took tug boat at 7 A.M. and towed to New York anchored of the Batterry. Chartered to go to Rondout after coal for Boston Went to Weehawken and took the tow as sunset.
column4: Execution Rock, New York, the Batterry, Weehawken

column3: The wind Easterly heavy shower in afternoon arrived in Rondout at 2 oclock P.M. wrote letter home
The wind Westerly and very hot. got a berth to the wharf in forenoon and commenced loading at noon.
The wind N. W. finished loading at 9 Am and towed out in the River to take the tow down
The wind very moderate and baffling took the tow at day light. to go down river.
The wind S.S.W cast of from the tow at Weehawken at 7 oclock and took a tug boat and towed through the Gates passed Execution Rock at one p.m.
The wind South abrest of the Little Gull Light House at 8 oclock A.M. and stemed the tide in the race untill noon. and got by. Passed Holmes Hole at 10 PM and Cross rip light at 10 night raining
column4: Little Gull Light, Holmes Hole, Cross Rip Light

column3: The wind S.S.W and foggy passed Pollock rip Light ship at 4am. at 8 1/2 Am the fog lighted and saw Nauset. anchored in Boston at 9 P.M. heavy rain storm with thunder and lightning.
The wind Westerly and very hot. towed into the berth to discharge very heavy thunder shower shower in the afternoon and evening.
The wind Easterly Commenced discharging coal
The wind Easterly finished onloading at noon and hauled of on flats ready to sail for home.
The wind S.S.E  got underway in Boston in the morning  passed Thatcher's Island at one PM Sighted Monheigan at 10 pm bearing North the wind hauling more Southerly.

The wind S.S.W abrest of Matinicus Rock Light at one A.m. passed duck Island at 8 Am foggy. run in Frenchman's Bay and have to 2 hours the fog scaled keped of and run in and anchored in Winter Harbor at 2 P.M. Settled with Capt Bickfordand left the Schr Harp took my dunnage out.
column4: Matinitcus Rock Light, Duck Island, Frenchman's Bay, Winter Harbor

column3: The wind Southerly and foggy.
The wind Southerly work in shop
The wind Southerly and foggy work in garden. wrote letters to James Chillcot and Secretary of Treasury D.C.
column18: James Chillcot, Secretary od Treasury D. C.

column3: Calm in morning work jig sawing finish for Geo. W. Whitaker. The wind outSoutherly and foggy in afternoon

The wind Southerly and foggy work in shop
The wind North West work in shop finished jib sawing for G. W. Whitaker
The wind North West went to Sabbath School in afternoon
The wind N.N.W. Commenced haying mowing in forenoon
The wind North West in forenoon and Southerly in afternoon mowed a little in morning polled in 8 stacks in afternoon recd letter from Mary A. Rosebrook
The wind Southerly poor hay day. work in shop
The wind Southerly and foggy. wrote letters to Mary Am. Rosebrook work in shop
The wind Easterly and foggy and rainy put down a mooring for a boat. and work in shop.

rainy the wind Southerly & Easterly work in shop. Making Crib

The wind Southerly hauled in 10 stacks of hay mowed in fore noon raked up in afternoon

The wind Northerly and went aroung Southerly in after noon got home at night.

Clear of very warm and pleasant. with the wind West fine breeze.

very moderate. and pleasant all day. The wind Southerly. wrote letter home

The wind North set reefed spanker and jib and gaftTopsail the wind hauled around Easterly at 8 pm took in all gaft topsail and flying jib. moderate winds and heavy sea
The wind South West set all sail the wind increasing Course E.S.E at 6 PM run under lower topsails and foresail very rough and overcast

The wind W.S.W. rainy in morning North West at night

No inflamation in hand but for some reason un noon to me, the doctors have decided not to trouble my hand to day
In Hospital at Leghorn so much run down by exceedingly great pain I am unable to get of my bed not having strength to stand alone

The wind North West Reed letter from Interpreter of Hospital at leghorn. And a speech from Eugene Hale M.C. Played at the Exhibition in evening.
The wind westerly. work in shop making pump boxes. In the evening played at Exhibition
The wind fresh North West. work in shop turing wheel hubs for Capt Nahum Rosebooks. in the evening played at the Exhibition in evening.
Southerly wind fresh breeze played at the Exhibition in evening heavy rain storm and blow
The wind northerly work about home
The wind Southerly and rainy
The wind Westerly work in shop.
The wind Westerly work on the Schr Sea Pigean Yawl boat
The wind southerly in forenoon. and snowy. In the afternoon the wind to the westward. work in shop turning.
The wind South East work one half day on A.G.Brooks. In afternoon work in shop repairing float rainy in evening
The wind Southerly Heavy rain all day work in shop
The wind North West work repairing the Schr Sea Pigeon boat finished work on her.
The wind Southerly and Easterly. went on Mark island Snow storm in afternoon
The wind Southerly moderate and warm work on AG Brooks played at the Hall in evening snow storm
The wind Easterly snowy in forenoon wrote letter to F Haines Briddford. Maine Went to the Hall and got My costume and Exhibition furniture
The wind North East took a sail boat and went to Cranberry Isles to see Capt Thomas Bunker about some notes. He gave for the Sea Flower. left home at 11 Am arrived at 2 1/2 P.M.
Calm in forenoon thick with snow. in afternoon cleared up and the wind North West.
The wind North West. Left Cranberry Isles at 5 oclock P.M. in boat with Capt Geo Leavy and son for home arrived at 7 1/2 oclock
The wind North. East. Snowy all day Went to C.Y.Bunkers and got his horse and came home.
The winds north East blustering snow storm
The wind Westerly fresh breeze and cold roads blocked with snow work in shop
The wind West North West in forenoon and hauled out South West went to Ellsworth with C.Y.Bunkers. horse
The wind S.S. East. rainy. Left Ellsworth for home at 2 oclock P.M. arrived at dark
The wind Southerly rainy in forenoon work in shop
The wind Easterly rainy in forenoon And in the afternoon went home with C.Y. Bunkers horse H.C. Guptills child died at 7 1/2 oclock PM.
Calm all day went to H. Msoules after Insurance Receipts a came home in afternoon
The wind Easterly and clear Homer Guptills child buried in afternoon
The wind Easterly work in shop in forenoon And in the afternoon settled acct with C.J. Guptill.
The wind South East and rainy all day. reed lettre from Lee Narraguagus Lodge. work in shop
The wind South East. and rainy. work in shop turning
The wind Southerly and overcast wrote letter to Galen H Smith and one to Narraguagus Lobdge Got a Bll floor home in forenoon and in the afternoon work on Alvin Foss dora
The wind North fresh breeze work in shop all day
The wind North in forenoon and Shoutherly in afternoon Reed letter from Narraguagus Lodge and one from Gale Smith went clamming in morning and work in shop
The wind South Easterly and clear went on Crow Island

The wind South by E. rainy and foggy Sent Postal card to Ellsworth American went to Cranberry Isles with C.J. Guptill in a boat to settle Estate of Joseph Moore. Arrived at 12 PM and settled in evening.
The wind N.N.East. rainy in morning. at 10 oclock AM cleared up. Bought the Schooner Sea Flower
The wind North East. Got in tow of a vessel and got towed part way across the bay. and left the vessel set sail and beat home arrived at noon
The wind North East, work in shop a part of the day and the remainder sawing wood
The wind North East in forenoon and heavy rain work in shop making desk wind South West in afternoon
The wind Northerly. and showery work at the wood pile
The wind Northerly. fresh breeze
The wind Noly East. work at the door splitting wood. The Schr Sea Flower arrived from Cranberry Isles frunuhich I tatre change Dr N. Pendleton died
The wind N.N.E. fresh breeze. Sent Postal Card to Wm. Dyer. work about home
The wind North East. Dr. N. Pendleton burried in afternoon took at home cutting wood.
The wind North East work at home in shop wrote to Hannah Bulger & Chas Hutchings Reed letter from George Leavy & Wm Dyer
The wind N.N.W. work on vessel putting piece of a wale on
The wind Southerly work on vessel. Capt B. C. Norwood Died at 11 oclock in the forenoon after a sickness of a little more wan and heur
The wind very moderate and pleasant South went to Mrs Saphia Hammonds funeral in ther afternoon at the Hall Winter Harbor
The wind South West work on board the Sea Flower fixing pumps
The wind Southerly Capt. B. C. Norwood burried went to funeral wrote to Capt. Geo Me. Leavy
The wind Southerly commenced Calking the vessel. in the afternoon
The wind Easterly. work all day Calking the Sea Flower. Reed letter from Mrs Bulger Heavy rain and blow at night
Calm all day foggy and showery work in shop
The wind Westerly work 3/4 of the day caulking wessel
The wind Easterly
The wind Southerly very hot Work all day calking vessel
The wind Southerly Foggy in the afternoon work on vessel
The wind Southerly and foggy work all day calking the Sea Flower At Sunset the wind came of to the Northward
The wind Northerly. Finished calcking the Sea Flower
The wind N.W. in forenoon & SW in afternoon at 2 PM got the Sea Flower underway and went up the bay for a load anchored of Tafts point at 6 oclock PM.

The wind Northerly in morning get under way ahead went to East Sullivan and chartered to load with lumber and bark for Salem. Southerly wind in afternoon. Took the Yawl boat went to stave Island and walked home
The wind Easterly and overcast left home in the afternoon & went to Stave Island took the boat and went to Sullivan and went on board the vessel
The wind Easterly high winds and heavy rain all day
The wind Easterly rainy and overcast all day went to Deputy Collector office in Sullivan for a new set of papers for the Schr Sea Flower
The wind North East. overcast in forenoon rainy in afternoon Waiting for a chance to get into the wharf
The wind North East rainy in forenoon hauled into the wharf
The wind Westerly Commenced loading with lumber got the hold about 2/3 full
The wind North west in forenoon S.W. in the afternoon finished filling the hold up with bark and took on deck load of bark for Salem
The wind North Easterly layed at the wharf tide mipper all day
The wind North East Got away from the wharf in the morning and got in home Shiped a new crew and went out in the afternoon and got to Deer Isles at dark.
The wind Northerly got underway at day light and at dark abrest of Pemaquid point becamed at .9 oclock PM the wind N.E. fresh breeze
The wind North East went into New Castle and anchored at eight oclock AM fresh breeze and. overcast at night rainy and thick
The wind North East and rainy all day laid at New Castle all day
The wind Southerly got under way in the forenoon and beat dower to the whales buck then went back and anchored.
The wind. South East got underway in New Castle at dark abrest the dry silnages very moderate. all day
The wind Southerly and Easterly moderate anchored in Salem at 4 oclock P.M. went into Derby wharf at dark
The wind Southerly hauled into the dock to discharge Consigned to Wm Pickering. discharged deck load in afternoon wrote letter home
The wind Westerly discharging cargo
The wind Southerly finished onloading in the forenoon hauled through the bridges at noon and made sail for home. Passed Thachers Island at 4:30 P.M. Midnight wind SW
At 6 oclock AM the wind Easterly with a shower and thick kept of for Portland and anchored at 2 oclock P.M. at dark moderate and foggy
The wind Easterly and foggy laid in portland had the vessels spars measured for a Main sail. At dark heavy rain squall wind West at 11 oclock cleared up got underway and went out for home.
The wind Northerly in morning then hauled around North East fresh breeze. passed Seguin at 3 AM At 2 oclock PM passed. White head the wind South West anchored at Fox Island at dark
The wind baffling and moderate South Easterly Anchored at Bass Harbor at dark
The wind South West got under way in the morning and arrived home at. 11 A.M.
The wind Easterly Commenced forming at noon worked the afternoon
The wind Easterly work all day planting potatoes
The wind Easterly finished planting potatoes peas squashes
The wind Easterly and in the afternoon rainy. Hired Wm Sargents horse and went to East Sullivan after a load for the Sea Flower. got back abt sunset.
The wind Northerly and showery. Filled water cask and work on board vessel getting ready to go away loading
The wind Northerly in morning S.W. in afternoon. got underway in fore noon and went up to East Sullivan to load with wood for Rockland
The wind South West. loaded a scow with wood but she did not fleet. Took her of migld tide
The wind Southerly got of one scow load of wood
The wind South West got of one scow load of wood
The wind very moderate Southerly got of one scow load of wood
Calm all the forenoon got of one scow load of wood finished loading. Got underway in the afternoon and went to Bar Harbor after a Main sail for the Sea Flower
The wind Southerly Laid at Bar Harbor untill 4 P.M for the arrival of Steamer Ulyses. Got Sail and got underway and went home arrived at 7 PM.
Calm all day and hot layed at anchor all day
Calm in forenoon bent the new mainsail. In ther afternoon the wind Westerly Got underway and out Anchored at Bass Harbor at midnight
The wind North W. went out of Bass Harbor in the morning. in the afternoon the wind S.W. by W. anchored at Fox Island at dark

Calm most all the forenoon. got underway at 10. Am the wind breezed up Easterly at 10.P.M. heavy rain anchored in Rockland at 2 oclock in the afternoon heavy rain wind E.N.East. went  shore and sold wood
The wind E.N.E drizzling rain went into the wharf at 8 oclock Am to discharge wood at night nearly discharged.
The wind Easterly moderate and thick with fog finished onloading in the morning and hauled of into the Harbor
The wind South East thick with fog and moderate got under way in the morning and started for Sullivan got down to Owls Head and drifted back to Rockland. Started again in afternoon to Fox Islands
column4: Sullivan, Owls Head, Rockland, Fox Islands

column3: The wind Southerly and fog very thick got underway at Fox Islands and went to Deer Isle.
The wind South West got underway in the morning and arrived at E Sullivan at dark.
The wind Southerly. and clear hauled into the wharf at noon Out side of the May Flower.  and took in a few cards of slabs across the May Flowers deck. loading for Boston.
The wind Southerly. got into the sharf at noon inside berth and worked the afternoon loading
The wind South West finished loading at 4 oclock in the afternoon. At 12 oclock at night the vessel floated and hauled of from the wharf
The wind Northerly made sail shore as came from the wharf. a little after 12 oclock AM: Got in home at 8 oclock Am. The wind South west in afternoon
The wind Southerly thick with fog. staid at home. put wood in shed and set up hogs heads to catch water
The wind North West got underway and went out for Boston at noon of Long Island head. at dark off Matinicus Rock.
The wind W N W in the morning headed W.S.W. no land in sight. At noon the wind S.S.W tacked ship and headed W. by. S. at 10 PM sighted Boon Island bearing west.
The wind S.S.W in morning passed Boon Island at day light. At noon in the wind West North West. run for Thaches Island passed it at 5 oclock P.M arrived in Boston at 10 P.M.
The wind North West in forenoon and hauled to the Eastward and around south west in the afternoon hauled into the wharf at night but no chance to discharge wrote letter home
The wind South West waiting all day for a chance to discharge
The wind North West very fresh breeze. commenced discharging cargo worked all day wrote letters to Daniel Ha'll Calais Also L.D.Parsons Bangor for freights
The wind North West in forenoon. Finished onloading at 10 A.M. got underway 11 Am for home at noon the wind W.S.W passed Thatchirs Island  at 5 oclock P.M. reefed mainsail fresh breeze.
The wind S.W. by W. heavy sea running Passed Monheigan at 7 oclock Am and White Head at 11. am in the afternoon the wind hauled out South. West. Arrived at Winter harbor at Midnight
The wind South West took the boat and went to Sullivan after freight but could get more. the wind Northerly in afternoon came home at night Reed letter from Lynam Toby Leo
The wind South West went on iron Bound and engaged a load of wood for Rockland
The wind Southerly took some wood ashore from the vessel and hauled it to the house
The wind Southerly put pipe in hugs heads for water wrote letter to Lynam Toby Sleo Portland Reed letter from Capt Thomas Bunker
The wind Southerly Got the Sea Flower underway and went to iron bound to load wood. Got one scow load of in the afternoon and one in the evening Loading for Charles Jacobs
The wind S.S.E and overcast work all day loading with wood at midnight got underway and went into Stave Island Harbor weather threatening.
The wind Southerly fresh. breeze and rainy all day went home by land.
The wind varibl all day weather hot and heavy rain squalls went back to Stave Island and went on board the Sea Flower
The wind South West and rough to much Sea to go back Iron Bound to take wood went back home.
The wind Southerly and hot. Went to Sullivan to the celebration with wife and child had boat race
Clam all the forenoon took of one scow load j hardwood for M Fros from his shore wind breezed up Southerly got under way and went to Iron bound anchored at dark.
Calm all the forenoon took of three scow loads of wood. the wind breezed up southerly got under way and went back to Mr Fosses shore and got another snow load.
The wind North East work all day loading finished at night
The wind South West got underway in forenoon and got in home at 11 oclock Am very fresh breeze
The wind Southerly and foggy work about home
The wind Southerly and foggy. hired N Hammonds horse and went to Ellsworth. for Counsil on the settlement of the estate offmure Lulling at night
The wind Southerly came home in fore noon. in afternoon went on Iron Bound to see Galen Smith very foggy at night
The wind Southerly went on Jordan Island to hire money back at night

The wind baffling went to Prospect Harbor early in the morning to hire money. Hired $100. of H D Cearmts back at 9 oclock. went on board of the Sea Flower and went out for Rockland anchored at Cranberry Isles at dark.

The wind N.N.W in morning went a shore on Cranberry isle to take up a note Emma M Spurling held she refused to went on suttons Islands to see her Attorney demanded it of him he refused. Went on board the wind breezed up Southerly got under waay and went out. anchored at Deer Isle
column4: Cranberry Isle, Sutton Islands, Deer Isle

column3: The wind N.N.W. got under way in the morning and went out In the afternoon the wind S.S.W anchored at Rockland into the wharf at midnight sold wood to A. Flewikensleo
The wind South West Commenced discharging wood in forenoon work remainder of the day. Had deed made put of apiece of Land to J.F. Kingsley
The wind Easterly finished onloading in forenoon received freight in afternoon and got ready to sail for home
The wind Easterly and foggy in morning at 10 afthe clock in the forenoon the fog lifted and the wind hauled to the Southard Got underway and Sailed for home. anchored at Cranberry Isles at sunset.
The wind very moderate and foggy. lay at anchor at Cranberry Isles all day. Wind Southerly
The wind S.S.W. thick with fog and rainy lay at anchor
The wind Southerly rainy in morning and foggy all day lay at anchor
Calm in morning and foggy at 9 Am the fog cleared up got underway. and got home at dark very moderate S.W. wind
The wind Southerly hauled into the wharf and discharged freight.
The wind North West on bent mainsail to lime
Calm all day went on Ironn Bound to pay Chas Jacobs for wood that I carried to Rockland. amount $39.54.
The wind Easterly and Rainy. wrote letters to Capt Thomas Bunker and J.T. Wallace Jr. Went to Prospect Harbor and took up note of $100. of H.D. Coombs
The wind Easterly. and overcast. Haed potatoes and cut wood at the door
Calm in the morning wrote lettesr to Curtis Stevens and Mefsrs S.C.Muney Sleo. wind Southerly in afternoon work in shop making mast wages. to place Sea Flowers main mark
The wind Southerly & foggy. Went to the Hall in the afternoon to a concert. to hear the White family sing.
The wind Southerly and rainy all day. work in shop making mast wages to splice vessels mainmast.
Calm in forenoon. Went to Mark Island to carry Mrs. Kingsley. in the afternoon the wind Southerly. helped J.F. Kingsley wape and put up tray.
The wind Easterly help J.F. Kingsley Mow and spread hay all the forenoon.
The wind Southerly. work Haying apart of the day for J.F. Kingsley. Bargained the Schr Sea Flower to Capt J.R. Hammond.
The wind South Easterly overcast and foggy in forenoon. work on the boardof the Sea Flower. putting wages around the mast. in the afternoon the fog cleared up.
The wind north West fresh breeze and pleasant went to Bar Harbor in my boat. and back Reed letter from Mejss S. C. Muney Sleo.
The wind North West in forenoon South West in afternoon
The wind North West in forenoon help J.F.K.And in the afternoon the wind South West work on vessel putting in tiller
The wind out Southly foggy in the evening rainy J.F. Kingsley get two loads of hay in barn
The wind moderate and foggy in morning then cleared up with the wind Westerly. Work with Wm Guptill in Shop doing black Smith work for vessel The wind out Southerly in afternoon
The wind North East and overcast. work on vessel Sold the Schr Sea Flower to Capt J.R. Hammond for $4.25
The wind Easterly and rainy work in shop all day.
Calm and foggy all day. Went to Ellsworth with Capt Crane. to see about J Mure Est Came home in the afternoon arrived at 8 oclock.
The wind Southerly and foggy help J.F.Kingsley put up some hay in the afternoon
The wind Southerly took all my provisions and dumage out of the Sea Flower. Work in shop in the afternoon.
The wind North East. moderate and foggy. and rainy work in shop
The wind N.E. thich with fog. work all day. for J. M Sargent on Schr Henrietta. rainy in afternoon
The wind Northerly work one half day on Schr Henrietta. rainy in afternoon
Calm in morning then the wind breezed up Southerly. Helped J.F. Kingsley get in hay in the afternoon foggy.

The wind North West. and thick with fog. Work apart of the day putting centre board in boat for my self. In ther afternoon cleaned up helped J.F.K. spread and open hay, reed letter from E.M. Spurlings
Calm in morning and clear. After the deer dried up. helped J.F. Kingsley open hay. The wind breezed up. Southerly In the afternoon help haul in hay.
The wind North West. in forenoon. Helped J.F.Kingsley. finish mowing. The wind Southerly in afternoon. Finished putting in centre board in boat for my self.
The wind Northerly in morning hauled around Easterly and Southerly fine hay day Helped J.F. Kingsley haul in three loads of hay the last for the season. As we finished haying
The wind Southerly Helped J.F. Kingsley hunt sheep in forenoon. And in ther afternoon got ready to go. Mackereling in my boat. went to schoodic pond and got a boat socle
Calm in the morning at 8 oclock the wind breezed up southerly. cut wood at the door and went berrying in the afternoon.
The wind South West. Went mackereling in boat. gone all day.
The wind Easterly. went mackereling
The wind Easterly. fresh breeze rainy in morning
Calm and foggy in the morning went to the Lowe Harbor after clams for mackerel bait. In the afternoon the wind Southerly. went mackereling
The wind Southerly and foggy went mackereling all day.
The wind S.S.West. went mackereling overcat.
The wind North North West fresh breeze all day went mackereling

Calm all the forenoon Went to Cranberry Isles in my boat with Charles Guptill to see Emma Spurling. got there abit 11 am. In the afternoon the wind breezed up South West. started for home at 3 arrived at 6 oclock.
The wind out Southerly very heavy sea rumming rainy and foggy went mackereling
The wind very moderate Northerly and westerly
The wind South West in forenoon Went in my boat mackereling a lone in the afternoon the wind North North West.
The wind South West Commenced work for William Guptill building house. J.F.Kingsley. boss
The wind SWest. work all day on Wm Guptill house Thunder & lightning in evening
The wind North North East wrote letter to Portland to Mejsis Sle. Muney &leo. Work all day for Wm. Guptill on house.
The wind North East Work all day on William Guptills house Raised the Walls
The wind Easterly and pleasant. Work all day on Wm Guptill house. Put in sleepers laid the under floor &e.
The wind North East and showery
Very moderate Northerly wind in forenoon. Went to the State Election at Town house Wind Southerly in afternoon. Bought land and Hotel of Frances E. Magune at Winter Harbor. writings done in evening.
The wind Southerly work all day for Wm Guptill on house Finished boarding the walls.
The wind Southerly work all day for Wm Guptill on his house. putting up studding wrote letter to Ellsworth to C.C. Burril and Reg of deeds.
The wind Southerly westerly and very hot. work all day for Wm Guptill on house. getting out finish.
The wind Southerly clear and hot. Work all day for William Guptill on on house. Put up the Main raflers and boarded the roof of the L Abner Tracy died at 11 oclock in Evening.
The wind Southerly work all day of Wm Guptill house. Foggy in afternoon Reef Postal card from C.C. Burril. Boarded the Gabel Ends and roof of house and put up stage

The wind Southerly and foggy. Abner Tracy burried in afternoon. Went to Schoodic to look after a Wreck supposed to be the Schr Harp. by the lumber drifting about. and a barrel with the name Schr Harp Stores.
The wind Southerly and figgy. Work all day for Wm Guptill on house Put up some staging and commence putting up finish.

The wind Southerly foggy and rainy in forenoon Went to Ellsworth to work Mr. L. Cranes. team to get the Hotel Insured In the afternoon cleared of Caine home in Evening Schr Harp found at sea water loged crew safe
The wind North West. Work for Wm Guptill day. Schr Harp arrived in morning full of water and rudder gone. Reed check from Capt J. R. Hammond. payment for Schr Sea Flower
The wind Southerly Went to Cherryfield with Capt Wm Handy to hore money on T Carlet got none Came home at night
The wind Southerly work all day for Wm. Guptill on house at night heavy rain.
Very fresh breeze Northerly. Work about home cutting wood. Got check cahed.
The wind from West to South West very fresh breeze.
The wind Southerly work all day for Wm Guptill on house wrote letters to Hancock  Co Paul Co. Ellsworth and Mrs Nary S Stanley
The wind South West. Registered a letter to Mrs Mary S. Stanley Cranberry Isles. Work all day making Window frames for Wm. Guptill
The wind South West work all day on William Guptills house. Finished making Window frames.
The wind West North West. very fresh breeze in morning Work all day for Wm Guptill on house making door frames and putting up returns.

The wind South East went to Ellsworth with Mr Cranes Thorse to see about raising money on Hotel & getting Mr Emery to appear at a Court of Probate for me to present my receipts to show the acct of Joseph Moore has been settled Took Wife with me Came back at night.
The wind Westerly work 7/8 of a day for Wm Guptill on house putting on finish Took 1/8 of a day to my self to talk with Frank Spurling about business matters.
The wind Southerly and warm: Went to Prospect for a ride with L.G. Canes horse.
The wind South West fresh breeze. Work all day for Wm Guptill on house putting in window frames. &c Paid all interest due on note. of Many A Rosebrook. by C. Stevens.
The wind North East. and pleasant. Went to Ellsworth with L.G. Cranes team to rais money on Hotel and to purchase furniture Came home in evening accompanied by Jennice L Kingsley.
The wind North East Overcast: Took the Schr Sea Flower with Capt J.R. Hammond and started for Ellsworth. to get furniture for Hotel Anchored at broard cove Oppostie Oak point at 7 oclock in evening.
The wind Southerly. Got underway in morning and arrived in Ellsworth at 9 oclock. Am. Bought and hauled down furniture the remainder of the day
The wind North East and rainy untill noon and cleared of with the wind Northerly. Hauled down furniture to the vessel in the afternoon.
The wind North West fresh breeze left Ellsworth at 9 oclock Am in the Sea Flower and got home at 4 oclock PM with furniture for the Hotel. Reed letters from Frank Spurling & Mary S Stanley
The wind North West fine breeze and pleasant
The wind South East. Work all day hauling furniture from vessel to Hotel with the help of Fred Crane
The wind South East and overcast. work in the forenoon hauling furniture from vessel. to house in the evening rainy and fresh breeze.
The wind South East. and heavy rain most all day. work in shop all day on guns for Aimasy Waistcoat and Edmond Sargent.
Very moderate with the wind South & Easterly went to Bar Harbor ro see Frank Corners abt building boats and to see the inside of some Hotel. Came back at night
The wind South Easterly and rainy work in shop on guns. &c
The wind Northerly. and very fresh breeze all day. Took the boad and started to go on Iron Bound but so much wind gave it up Received a letter from C. C. Burril
The wind Northerly in forenoon. Went on Iron Bound with J.F. Kingsley. In the afternoon the wind Southerly
The wind Northerly Went to Ellsworth with  accompanied by my wife via Franklin to raise money on Hotel stoped at the Hancock House.
The wind North East. Heavy rain with w. little snow untill 2 oclock P.M. then started for home arrived at 7 P.M.
The wind Northerly. dug potatoes in forenoon. And in the afternoon Getting ready to move.
THe wind Westerly. work apart of the forenoon for G. W. Tracy moving partition. And in the afternoon took Possession of the Hotel and moved in: Reed letter from C. C. Burril
The wind Southerly work all day at the Hotel Setting up stove and moving thing over from the Old home. ar night rainy
The wind North East. work about. the house. Reed a letter from Cept E V. Lynam
Calm all day. First company in house for dinner.
The wind North East and heavy rain all day. work about the house. Wrote letter to E.C.Smith Boston & E. V. Lynman Long Pong
The wind South West. washing and putting away furniture all day Received letter from C C Burril.
Calm all day Hauled wood from the old place and repaired the cook stove. At night rainy
The wind North East and snowy. all day wrote letter to Mijsrs Maymard Gough &Co. work all day in house painting furniture Received letter from Curtis Stevens
The wind Northerly went to Prospect. and West Gouldsboro to see about money matters.
The wind North West. wrote letter to C.C. Burril work in the house cleaning up
The wind Northerly. in forenoon and Westerly in afternoon.
The wind Southerly. very fresh breeze. Went to West Gouldsboro and took the stage and went to Ellsworth to see about. getting money. on Hotel. Reed letter from Maynard Gough &Co. afternoon rainy
The wind Northerly and clear. took the Gtage to West Gouldsboro and came home Wrote letter to C.C. Burril Ellsworth
The wind Southerly Blasting rock in Highway
The wind north West wrote letters to H. D Coombs. and E V Lynam reed letter from C. C. Burril. work all day in houses with R Rand painting and varnishing furniture

The wind Easterly in morning then hauled out South. Work with R. Rand. in house painting furniture In the afternoon very fresh blow. heavy storm work a part of the afternoon. turning in shop turning for Reuben Rand.
The wind Westelry very fresh breeze. Work in the shop turning and jigsawing For R Rand.
The wind Westerly fresh breeze.
The wind Southerly fresh breeze and rainy at night. Got ready to go gunning in forenoon. and worked prying up store. in the afternoon
The wind N.N.West. wrote letter to J. A Milliken Cherryfield. Work hauling stone around the house. reed letters from Thomas Bunker Cranberry Isles. And C C Burril at Ellsworth.
The wind South West. work in forenoon blowing rock for house. Work in the afternoon laying floor for A Foss. and in the evening wrote Bill of State for Jame M Sargent
The wind South West. went gunning in forenoon mended store in afternoon. Received Postal Card from J. A. Milliken. Drafter a boat for Edward Kingsley.
The wind South very fresh breeze and a very big storm. work in house moving sink and making changed. in cook room
The wind North East. Work in house making shelves &c Reed letters from Stephen Southward Mejsrs S. C. Muney &Co. Pothand & C. C. Burril
The wind North East. Went to the Lower Harbor after Capt Cranes team to go to Ellsworth
The wind Northerly wrote letters to Stephen Southard Thomas Bunker & Mejsrs S Le Muney &Co. went to Ellsworth with L. G. Cranes horse after money got $500.
The wind Northerly. wrote Card to C. Stevens Came home.
The wind Southerly hauled wood from the Old place. and work about home
The wind Southerly fresh breeze. wrote letter to Curtis Stevens Mejsrs M Gallent. and H. D. Coombs. work about home.
The wind Southerly showery. work apart of the day for A. Foss. on the inside of his house.
Calm and pleasant. all day. Worked with a mason topping out chimney in the L. reed letter from Mejsrs M. Gallent &Co wrote one to H. H. Smallidge
The wind South Easterly and rainy
The wind North West work hauling stone around the house.
The wind Northerly work about home reed letters from Mejrs S. C. Muney &Co. Curtis Stevens and Dr S M Lumun
The wind Northerly. Work with a Mason topping out chimney
Very Moderate wind North West Work with Daniel Bickford topping out chimney. wrote letter to Capt S.L. Tracy.
The wind northerly Killed my Hog with the help of Caled Pendleton
The wind Easterly and clear. Painted chimneys and commenced taring roof of house. Received letter from S. L. Tracy.
The wind Easterly and overcast
The wind Easterly very fresh breeze and apart of the day rainy Work in the house. making bed slats. &c.
The wind Easterly and rainy went to West Gouldsboro to carry a runner. reed four boarders Regs letter to Curtis Stevens with $25. Enc
The wind Southerly and rainy i the morning work abt the house
The wind Easterly work in the forenoon putting underpin ing under the wing of the house. in the afternoon rainy and snowy wrote letter to Mijsus S.C.Muney &Co Mras Proctur Smallidge
The wind North West and cold Snowy work about home
The wind Northerly and cold split stone for the house in fore noon and work for Capt J.R.Hammond on Sch Sea Flower in the afternoon
The wind Northerly and cold Dr Inman Dentist left.
The wind South West. Work all day hauling stone around the house.
The wind North West and moderate. Work putting stone under the platform of house. Reed letter from Curtis Stevens
The wind Southerly fresh breeze send at night very heavy rain and wind. Work in the house putting up door bell &c.
The wind North West and cloudy work with William Tracy & Daniel Bickfors putting underpinning under the house.
The wind North West. and moderate. work banking up the house.
The wind South West Snowy in fore noon wrote letter to Chas C. Burris. Work abt home.
The wind West North West and very pleasant.
The wind moderate Northerly and warm Hauled up coal from wharf to the House in forenoon. And made Cart Alletree for Haines Bickford in afternoon
The wind East.N.East Snowy all day. wrote letter to American office for Bill poster printed for a douer for Christmas. work on furniture all day. At night rainy
The wind North West. Work about home all day.
The wind South Snowy and rainy all day worked apart of the forenoon on board of the A.G. Brooks putting a scuttle in the cabin floor. in the afternoon setting up beals
The wind North West very fresh breeze. Send postal cards to Andrea Laffin Hancock & Choes Burril work a part of the day putting fore foot on Schr A.G. Brooks
very moderate all day wrote postal cards to Andrea Laffin & Chas Cale. work apart of the day on the A.G.Brooks
The wind W.SWest. and pleasant.
The wind South West. fresh breeze putty glass in door and windows work apart of the day for Geo Tracy on dora.
The wind Northerly. wrote letters to Geo W. Boyley & G.W.Whittoker. Work apart of the day for G. W. Tracy in evening wrote Bill of Sale of Sea Flower for J R Hammond to James M. Sargent.
The wind Southerly at night rainy Work apart of the day for J. D. Harrington building stairs
The wind Northerly Went to Ellsworth. with J. D. Harrington to see about getting Music to the Back Christmas. Engaged Laffins Orchestra Hancock.
Very Moderate all day with the wind North West. Came home in the afternoon.
The wind N.N.W. moderate work about home thermometer 24Â°
The wind Northerly Thermometer at 8 oclock 26Â°
The wind North West thermometer 32Â° in morning work about home getting ready for Christmas ball and supper.
The wind North West and very fine weather the thermometer in morning 28Â° Got up a Ball and Supper in the Evening 16 couple in all.
The wind Northerly Thermometer in the morning 30Â° work all day cleaning up rooms dishes &e caused by a large crowd Christmas.
The wind North West thermometer in the morning 34Â° work apart of the day for JDHairington

The wind very moderate and warm south cast Thermometer in morning 34Â° being placed on the North side of the house in the shade. work all day for JDHarrington foushed the legt up his store went to Prospect Exhibition
The wind Northwest and very warm and pleasant for the time of year the Thermometer at 41Â° above 0 work about home. cutting wood &c.
The wind North East. Thermometer 28Â° overcast.

The wind N.N.W. the thermometer stood at 23Â° This day not the particle of snow to the seen and has not been but one or two days sleighmg for the winter The Harbor and coves all free from Ice and the ground as bare as in july. Worked all day for J. D. Harrington. finishing the chamber over his store.. Had for boarders J.D. Harrington Wife and child. and a few Tromcient. ones
NA
NA

The wind North fresh breeze the thermometer at 8 am 10Â° above 0 the thermometer hangs on the north side of the house in the shade and will be noted in the morning unless otherwise specified. Gave T. R. Hammond to notes of $100 each for one of J. M. Sargent and Geo Wescott. Work apart of the day for J D Harrington. went to wharf meeting in the evening
The wind North East thermometer 18Â° above zero work apart of the day for J D Harrington
The wind Northerly fresh breeze in morning Thermometer 8Â° above zero. and at 9 oclock in the evening it was down to 0 Work at the door cutting wood Went to a religious meeting in Evening
The wind South East Thermometer in the morning down to zero. at night Thermometer 28Â° above in the evening a terrific storm of snow rain and wind Work about home
The wind West North West Thermometer in morning 37Â° above and at night 0Â° Work about home.
The wind North West.Wind moderate. Thermometer at 8 am 4Â° above 0 at night 10Â° above. Went to the Lower Harbor and back in dora.
The wind North The Thermometer 9Â° below zero Went up the stream cutting fire wood Thermometer 4Â° above at night
The wind North West. Thermometer 14Â° below 0 In the afternoon the Thermometer at zero Work around home. Recd letter from Thomas Bunker & Card from F. Haines Biddeford

The wind Northerly and moderate snowy all the fore noon Thermometer at 25Â° above zero work apart of the day for J D Harrington Wrote letters to Thomas Bunker & CC Burrill + postal card to F. Haines Biddeford
The wind Easterly Thermomteter 34Â° above Went up the stream in woods cutting fire wood. In the evening heavy storm

The wind Easterly after 1 am and a heavy riving rain storm. at day light wind eased. Thermometer 40 above work about home clearning out the cellar drain put the cellar was full of water went to a religious meeting evening
The wind North West very moderate The Thermometer 32Â° degrees up to 40Â° above zero. Work about the house. repairing sash and putting in glass.
The wind North West Thermometer from 32Â° up to 40 degrees very pleasant.
The wind South East The Thermometer from 33Â° to 39 above. Work helping JDH set up getting ready to house keeping In the Evening work on G. W. Tracys floor planning it.

The wind North West Thermometer at 32 untill night when it fell a little Work getting wood up of the wharf and helping J D Harrington Mr J D Harrington + wife + child left us. from C C Burrill Recd letter
The wind North West Thermometer from 10 above down to zero. Work apart of the forenoon for J D Harrington and the afternoon for G W Tracy planning floor. Dancing school at my house in evening
The wind North West The Thermometer from 0 to 6 above. Wrote letter to C C Burrill Finished planning & painting floor for G. W. Tracy.

Calm or nearly all day Thermometer in morning 6Â° above zero in the afternoon 36 above. Helped J F Kingsley cut ice in the forenoon and in the afternoon work about home Went to a Religious meeting in the Evening
The wind Westerly Thermometer from 32Â° to 38 above zero. Work about home cutting wood. Putting up stove in office making an handle &e Recieved letter from S L Tracy.
The wind Southerly and pleasant. The Thermometer 38 degrees to 42 degrees above zero. Not any snow on the ground to be seen
The wind South Easterly. moderate and rainy all day. Thermometer 42 1/2 degrees above zero Work in the house joinering Commenced making counter dancing school at the house in the Evening
The wind Southerly moderate rain storm all day Thermometer 38 degrees above zero Wrote letter to S. L. Tracy made cupboard for g D Harrington

The wind Southerly Thermometer at 36Â° above in morning and drizling rain The ground as bare as in July. at 10 am commenced snowing Helped G F Kingsley fill his ice house at 3 pm the Wind N.W. at 9 pm Thermometer down to zero and very blustering snowing dancing school at my house in the evening
The wind North West. Thermometer 2 degrees below zero. Work in the house jobbing Taking the Officefor a work shop
The wind Westerly. Thermometer 10 degrees above zero work in house making Counter.
The wind Easterly. work in house making over a chair into a barbers chair for Warren Smith.
The wind Westerly Thermometer up to 35 degrees above zero.

The wind Easterly rainy in morning afterward snow and rain Went to West Gouldsboro With Wm Sargents house to see about the new mail Route came home in the afternoon dancing school at my house in the evening Thermometer at 9 pm 16Â° above
The wind North West Thermometer 5 degrees above zero in the morning and 12 degrees above at night. Work most of the day in J F Kingsleys shop. Turning. Went to Tempranes Exhibition in Evening.
The wind North West. Thermometer at zero in the morning + 14 above at night Work about home all day

Calm all day, The Thermometer 2 degrees above in the morning Wrote letter to the Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co of Bangor. Work in the house making liba Recd letter from Capt E. V. Lynam. Long pond. Went to a religious meeting in the Evening.
column34: Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co was definitely a difficult phrase in one of previous journals, couldn't get penobscot

column3: The wind E.N. East. Thermometer 14 degrees above zero. A little snow in the middle of the day. Work on the out side of the house. a part of the forenoon trying to stop a leak.
The wind Northerly Thermometer from 8 degrees up to 18 degrees above zero. Work in house finishing the Office
The wind Westerly Thermometer 16 degrees above zero in the morning
Calm all day. The Thermometer from 16 degrees above zero to 34 above very pleasant. Finished joiner work in the Office and had it primed.

The wind Northerly + moderate Thermometer from 28 degrees to 35 above zero. Wrote letter to H.D. Coombs Augusta for a commission as Justice of the Peace. Helped J.K. Kingsley shingle the roof of his ice house Recd letter from Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co.

The wind Westerly Thermometer at 38 degrees above zero. Went in the woods often Cut timbers in the forenoon. And went a Crannberrying in the afternoon Not a particle of snow to be seen but Ice in swamps
Calm all day Thermometer at 44 degrees above zero. Wrote letter to C C Burrill Cut wood at the door Went to Dick Martz. Exhibition in evening
The wind Southerly Thermometer 39 degrees above zero. Went clamming and floundering in forenoon And in the afternoon had the office grained and in the Evening went to a Religious Meeting
The wind North East and rainy The Thermometer 35 degrees above zero. No snow to be seen Painted the floor of the office Recd letter from H.D. Coombs Augusta
The wind North East and snowy all day The Thermometer 20 degrees above zero all day.
The wind Northerly Thermometer from 18 to 20 degrees above zero. Snow enough to make quite decent sledding the first for the season except one day Work about home.

The wind West Thermometer at 20 degrees above zero. Wrote letters to American Office Ellsworth and Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co Went on sail in yatcht Water Lily Capt R Pendeleton Rect letter from C.C. Burrill
The wind South Westerly Thermometer 32 above zero Clerk for J.D. Harrington for him and his wife to go to Colombia
The wind North West Thermometer from 7 above up to 20. Clerk for J D Harrington
Calm all day. Thermometer down to zero. Clerk for J.D. Harrington a part of the day until the arrival of him + his wife

Very light Northerly wind. Thermometer at 20 degrees above in the morning in the shade but gradually risind toward middle of the day. Wrote to H.D. Coombs + D A Ray Recd letter from Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co
The wind Southerly Thermometer 24 above zero. Went to Ellsworth in the afternoon with J.D. Harrington stoped at the Lake House
The wind Northerly got fifty dollars of C.C. Burrill. Left Ellsworth at 11 am took dinner with R.A. Heath came home in the afternoon Thermometer 12 degrees above.
The wind North West Thermometer at 20 above zero Wrote letters to A J Baker M.D. Postal Cards to N.H. Higgins and Galen H Smith.
The wind Southerly in the afternoon and evening snowy. Thermometer at 24 above got supper for a dance at the ending of a dancing School
The wind North East. Thermometer at 20 above Recd Lizzie May Ulmers dramatic Company. for boarders Recd letter from C.C. Burrill
The wind East fresh blow Thermometer at 20 above about the house waiting upon the company
The wind South East rainy most of the day Thermometer 38Â° above zero Recd an appointment from Secretary of state as justice of the peace
The wind North West. Thermometer 44Â° above zero.
The wind North West Thermometer made moddle for a new boat.

The wind North West. Thermometer 34 degrees above zero. Registered letter to Treasurer of State of Maine for a commission as justice of the Peace. wrote letter to R. Fickett + Son Mulbridge Recd letter from H.D. Coombs Postal card from Lizzie May
The wind North West Thermometer 36Â° above zero Work apart of the day mending stove
The wind South West Thermometer 40 degrees above zero. Recd letters from R Fickett + son Work in J F Kingsleys shop building boat for myself
Thermometer 24 above zero Wind North Work apart of the day on boat.

The wind Southerly Thermometer 32 above Work all day for Wm Handy splicing Sea Pigeons mainmast Wrote letters to Myses Maynard Gough & Co & R Fickett + Sons. Recd commission from the State as justice of the peace.
The wind South Easterly Thermometer at 40 degrees above zero. And heavy rain storm all day.
The wind N.N. West. and rainy all day Thermometer 40 degrees above Work on a boat building one fore myself.
The wind North West Thermometer 29 above 0 Work in forenoon on my boat. and in the afternoon for Capt. Wm Handy on Sea Pigeons mast Recieved letter from R. Fickett + Sons.
The wind Southerly Worked apart of the forenoon for Wm Handy on vessels mast. In afternoon went to Lower Harbor and took Mr Cranes boat of to go to Bar Harbor next day apart

The wind very moderate Southerly and foggy. Thermometer 38 above 0 Went to Bar Harbor with Chas Pendleton and L G Cranes boat after Lizzie May Ulmers Dramatic Company. Got home with them at 5 oclock pm Went to Theatre
The wind North West and the Thermometer 52 degrees above zero in the Shade on North Side house Recd letter from Mysrs Maynard Gough + Company
The wind Moderate N.W. Thermometer 48 degrees above 0  Wrote letter to Messes Maynard Gough + Co. Worked a part of the day in J.K. Kingsleys shop on a boat building for my self.
The wind South West Thermometer 46 above zero Wind hauled around North West in afternoon
NA
NA
NA
NA
NA
NA
The wind Southerly Thermometer 38Â° above Went to Lower Harbor and Mark Island Recd letter Stephen Southard. Via Chas Norris
The wind Easterly fresh breeze Thermometer 33Â°  a big snow storm the largest there has been for the Winter. and very blustering. Work apart of the day for J.K. Kingsley on on boat for James Knight.

The wind North West Thermometer 38Â° above went Court in forenoon case where B. T. Sowle arrested Fred Rice for disturbing the school verdict for Soule. Rice fined $200 & east. E. Colemans trial justice. In afternoon attended court in Hall in case B.T. Soule arrested G.L. Norwood for calling him a damn hypocrite. E.C. Caves Trial justice. my self councelor for G.L. Norwood court adjourned untill tomorrow at 9 oclock for Evidence Recd letter from Portland + Machias Boat Co.
The wind N.W. fresh breeze Thermometer 36Â° above zero Attended court at 9 am as per adjournment. any self Councellor for defendant B. T. Sowle Councellor for himself verdict for defendent

Wrote letter to E.W. Cleaves The wind North West Thermometer 18 above Went to West Gouldsboro. and took the stage & Went to Ellsworth after money got $100 of C C Burrill Was qualified as justice of the peace
The wind North West Thermometer 20 above Sent Post Office order to Wm. H. Earl from Ellsworth to Bangor. In the afternoon came to West Gouldsboro
The wind South West Thermometer 40Â° Came home at noon Mrs. Nathan Hammond died about 7 oclock pm
The wind Southerly. Thermometer 40Â°

The wind South West early in the morning blowing a gale and hauled to the West Thermometer 20Â° above worked apart of the day For J.F. Kingsley. Hauled out a load for my self Acknowledged deed for Mrs. Mary W Joy warantee deed

The wind West. Thermometer 36Â° degrees attended the funeral of Mrs. Lucinda Hammond Wrote letter to Freeland Rosebrook Recd letter from Chas Shaw Recd letter heads & envelopes printed from the American Office
The wind Southerly Thermometer 40Â° above zero. work apart of the day in J.F. Kingsleys shop.
The wind Easterly Thermometer 36Â° Wrote letters to Mysrs M Gallant &Co Henry Benson Chas Shaw & Geo Westcott Eldridge & Perry Commenced planking boat for my self
The wind N.N. East. Thermometer 36Â° above. Bought a horse of George Wescott
The wind N.N. East. and Snowy all day. Thermometer 33 above wrote letters to S.C. Forsaith
The wind Northerly Thermometer 35Â° above and rainy all day.
The wind Northerly Thermometer 36Â° and overcast, misty. Work apart of the day on my boat and commenced making Pile driver for Gerrish Tracy &Co.

The wind Northerly and overcast Thermometer 34Â° above Wrote letter to Myses. R Fickett + Sons. Work all day on Pile driver for Gerrish and Tracy. Recd letter from Eldridge & Perry. Alice Tracy died about midnight
The wind Northerly Thermometer 46Â° Work all day on Pile Driver

The wind North North East and drizzling rain all day Thermometer from 34Â° to 40Â°  Work in the forenoon for J.D. Harrington putting up Iron sink. Mys. Alice Tracy burried in the afternoon Recd Postal Card from Mysrs. Maynard Tough &Co
The wind North East. and rainy and rainy all day. Thermometer 38Â° Finished Pile driver for Gerrish Tracy &Co. Wrote letter to Bertha Smallidge
The wind N.N.East. Thermometer 36Â° Wrote letters to Reg of deeds Mysrs Cobb Wight & Norton Work about home.
The wind Northerly Thermometer 34Â° rainy all day by spells
The wind North East. Thermometer 40Â° jobbing abt home.
The wind South West and clear Thermometer 36Â° above work most all day on boat for my self
The wind Southerly and foggy in forenoon Thermometer 40Â° degrees Work all day on boat for my self

The wind Southerly and rainy foggy. Thermometer 38Â° degrees Went to Prospect Harbor to Carry Wm. Handy Finished planking boat at J.F. Kingsleys shop Recd letters from Mysrs S.C. Forsaith & Co. and R. Fickitt & sons.
The wind Easterly fresh breeze and big rain storm the Thermometer 39. Moved boat from J.F. Kingsley shop to my house in morning
The wind very moderate Southerly Thermometer 44Â° Wrote letters to Genl Agt Portland Bangor & Machias Steamboat Co. and Capt. David Robinson Put gunwails on boat.
The wind North Overcast. Thermometer 48Â° Went to Sullivan to Cary Herbert E Tracy and accompanied by his Brother Charles E Tracy
The wind Northerly and fresh breeze. Thermometer 43 Filled out application for Bounty Claim for Mrs. Mary Tracy
The wind Southerly Thermometer 42 degrees. Painted boat inside.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 45Â° bought waggon of William Guptill
The wind Southerly Thermometer 42Â° Went to Ellsworth with my horse after sheeting for bed
The wind North West Thermometer 55Â° Got the goods and came home in afternoon

The wind Southerly and clear. Thermometer 55Â° degree above. Caulked and painted boat Recd postal card from A.J. Chapman Esq Bangor. Filled out and acknowledged the Signing of an application for Pension for Nancy Joy.

The wind Southerly and foggy Thermometer 51Â° at noon Went to prayer meeting Preaching in forenoon. And in the afternoon went to Baptism in this place. Hannah Newman, Augustus Newman, Alphena and Daniel Bickford, Mary Ann Giles, Emma Jane Myrick, and Joseph Bickford In the Evening went to meeting of the Lords supper by Wm Whicken
The wind Westerly. The Thermometer 56Â° above Puttied the boat and painted her Bought pig of F Toft 5 weeks old
The wind North East. Thermometer 54Â° Wrote letters to Mrs Proctor Smallidge, S.C. Forsaith, &Co, Thomas Bunker & E.A. Baker Recd Hotel Register from Mysrs Maynard &Co.
The wind Southerly and wet and foggy Thermometer 51Â° work all day on boat putting in seals &e
The wind Southerly and foggy Thermometer 48 Wrote letters to Capt H.C. Guptill Calais work a little while on boat.
The wind South Easterly and foggy Thermometer 50 work about the house all day
The wind South East. and rainy in morning Thermometer 50 degrees. Wrote letters to S.C. Muney &Co. Worked on boat apart of the afternoon. Recd letter from S.C. Forsaith Red Speech from Han E Hale
The wind South East foggy and rainy in morning Thermometer 50 degrees afternoon cleared up.
The wind North East and rainy Thermometer 57 hauled one load wood
The wind North East and heavy rain all day. Thermomter 49Â° wrote letter to Mrs. Martin Pendleton at Lynn Recd letter from Geo Bagley work about the house. C.J. Guptill made each as school agt.
The wind Easterly and overcast. Thermometer 46Â°, fixed pen for pig and hauled wood from Esqr Rands meadow
The wind South West and clear. Thermometer 54Â° Cut wood at the door wrote letter to G.W. Bagley
The wind Southerly Thermometer 50Â° hauled stone all day grading in front of house.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 52 foggy. Grading in front of house.
The wind Southerly and foggy Thermometer 48Â° Went to Religious meeting in Evening
The wind Baffleing or Calm all day and the Thermometer 55 degrees Went to Steuben to see abt getting lumber and to Millbridge to see R. Fickett & sons Came back at night
The wind Westerly Thermometer 56. Work in the house making Curtain Sticks and fixing windows. Had new Shoes put on the Horse. Recd letter from Mrs. J.D. Fernald Boston
The wind North West Thermometer 56Â° Went to Ellsworth. with my horse after dishes and Table linnes
The wind Easterly. and clear Thermometer  54 Came home from Ellsworth in afternoon.
The wind Easterly and rainy Thermometer 52Â° wrote letter to Mysrs Eldridge & Perry. Sold Massiah Southards horse to Mr W.F. Vose.

The wind South West Pleasant Thermometer 53 Wrote letter to J.D. Femeld and Stephen Southard. Went to Bar Harbor in my boat + back. Recd letters from S.R. Niles advertising agents. Boston + Abraham French + Co. Dealers in Crocking & glass ware.

The wind North West. Thermometer 50Â° Went up to the Shore for Baptism but candidate failed to come forward. At night went to the Marsh to be ready for a start To go to Steuben after lumber for outside hog
The wind Northerly & The Thermometer 49 Went to Steuben and got a load of boards and back to West Bay. had them planed and came home at night had Calvin Tracys horse with mine
The wind N.N.West Thermometer 41Â° degrees Wrote letters to Eldridge &  Perry also Rev Mr. Tripp of Surry
The wind South Easterly and the Thermometer 55Â° Commenced building platform around the house Filled out an application for pension for F.P. Gerrish

South East wind overcast Thermometer. Wrote letters to American Office Chas Burrill (of Ellsworth) and F.W. Webber (Cambridgeport) Daily Courier (Lowell)  Mrs. Geddy. Commenced laying platform around house
The wind Southerly and Thermometer 52 finished laying platform on west side of the house

The wind very moderate all day. Thermometer 58Â° Work on platform around house Recd letters from E.A. Baker Springfield Republican Cambridge Conicle Boston Courier L.S. Tripp of Surry and from American Office

The wind North East in morning hauled around South East in afternoon Went to the baptism of three persons. Mrs Julia Bickford Mrs Direxa Guptill and Mrs. Alma Moon by Mr Whitten The Thermometer 61Â° degrees high in the shade North side of the house.
The wind South East. Thermometer 56Â° Work around the House
The wind S.S. East Thermometer 49Â°  Wrote letters to S.C. Forsaith E.A. Baker Mrs. J.D. Fernald
Calm and overcast in forenoon Started for Bar Harbor with Capt R. Pendleton Thermometer 45 at 11 am Took the wind North West and heavy rain came back in afternoon
The wind North East fresh breeze and rain Squalls Thermomter 55 Work around the house recieved letters from Alice E Smith Rockland Mary Smallidge and D.W. Joy
The wind North East, in morning fresh breeze at 10 am wind moderate Thermometer 54Â° Went to Bar Harbor With R Pendleton after Mary Smallidge wrote letters to Mrs J.D. Fernald
The wind South Easterly Thermometer 49Â° Went to Ellsworth with my horse accompanied by my wife after dishes. Got a load of dishes and came back to West Gouldsboro. and stoped to Mrs. E Kingsley
The wind Southerly & foggy Wrote letter to American Office. and came home in forenoon Thermometer 55 degrees.
The wind South West Thermometer 60. Work about home on the house
The wind from N.W. to S.W. and the Thermometer 62 Wrote letter to F.W. Webber. Cambridgeport Recd letter from Boston Home Journal. Hauled wood from the wharf for T. H. Smallidge work around the House
The wind North West. Thermometer 65 degrees Work around the House
The wind Easterly at night Foggy Thermometer 56 wrote a Lease of James Banett peace to Nahum Fittzjerald Recd letter from Salem Post.
The wind Very moderate all day Southerly and the Thermometer 69 Working on water closet
The wind Southerly Thermometer 52Â° degrees Work on water closet. recd letters from Officer of Salem day Evening Express S H Paritin Advertising age Cincinnati
The wind Southerly Thermometer 56 degrees
The wind Southeast and foggy Thermometer 55 Work on water closet with the help of Frank Summer
The wind Southerly & Foggy Thermometer 55Â° Had Parlor papered by Frank Summer and worked around the House Wrote letter to Eldridge & Perry. and Recd letter from Mrs J.D. Fernald
The wind Southerly and foggy Thermometer 55 Work on water closet. Recd dishes from Eldridge & Perry by Express

The wind North West and fresh breeze and the Thermometer 55 degrees Work on house getting ready for boards Recd letters from Eldridge & Perry of Ellsworth and Hombmas & Dennison of Brewer and from the Hotel world
The wind from W.N.W. to S.W. very fresh breeze. Thermometer from 50Â° 60 Put down carpet in parlor and got Parlor and Office ready for use. and work around the House generally.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 54 Commenced farming in morning and finished at night with the help of Charles Harrington at night very heavy rain
The wind North East and very heavy rain until 8 oclock Cleaned up with the wind North West Thermometer 52Â° degrees above
The wind baffling and moderate all day. Thermometer 52 degrees Wrote letter to American Office work all day on house. on water closet.
The wind North East and rainy all day Thermometer 50 degrees Wrote letter to C.C. Burrill laid carpet in chamber Went Birch Harbor at night to Carry John McFarland of Lamoine and brought him back

The wind Southerly and by spells Showery Thermometer 52 degrees Took Wm Rands saw to the Lower Harbor with the help of Wm Rand + John Grover and loaded her with wood 5 cords got back to Henry's Cove at dark and grounded the Scow

The wind Southerly and Showery Thermometer 53Â° Went to tthe West Shore to Cary Frank Summer and his tool chest hauled 7 loads of wood from the Sein house Recd letters from Boston Times + Boston daily Transcript
The wind Southerly and thick with fog all day Finished hauling wood from Scow to the door at noon Worked on Liberty pole apart of the afternoon After Supper went to Prospect Harbor with my Honey
The wind Southerly and Foggy. Thermometer 53Â° made sign board for R Rand to paint Eureka House Recd letters from Boston Transcript Office Wrote letters to Frank Woodard
The wind Southerly and Foggy Thermometer 56 at night the fog scaled up.
The wind Southerly fresh breeze Thermometer 54Â° work all day around the House hauling gravel.
The wind Southerly & foggy Thermometer 58Â° Went to Sullivan to Mr Pettengills to see Abbie Crabtree wrote letter to Eldridge & Perry. Went to prospect at night. Recd letter from Emma M. Spurling
The wind Southerly fog cleared all the vessels went out Went to Prospect got Bbl flour. Thermometer 59 degrees Bought waggon of H.D. Coombs

Calm in morning and in afternoon wind Southerly Thermometer 70 degrees Recieved letters from American Office & Franck Woodard of Ellsworth. Had a Clapping match in afternoon and a dance in evening at House got wagon home of H.D. Coombs
The wind Southerly Thermometer 69 degrees work all day with horse grading in front of the house Wrote letter to E.A. Baker
The wind moderate Easterly Thermometer at noon 75 degrees in shade finished grading aroung the house and worked apart of the day leveling up the Grounds.
The wind fresh breeze and heavy rain all day Thermometer 48 degrees
The wind Southerly and foggy Thermometer 58 Work around the house. whitewashing & painting and fixing up things in general.
The wind Southerly and foggy in morning at night the wind W. Thermometer 60 degrees. Painted Hall floor and work around the house. Wrote letter to Emma Spurling.
The wind North West Painted hall floor and put down carpet, white washed and fixed up out buildings and leveled grounds &e. Thermometer 60 degrees
The wind North West and very fine weather Thermometer 68 degrees Work about the house put down the Carpet &e
The wind Southerly East Thermometer 60 degrees Work about the House all day. Put Sign up.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 84Â° at 5 p.m. Wrote letter to G.W. Bagley went to Prospect in afternoon. worked apart of the day making flying boom for the Schr Black Warrior

Calm in morning at 8 oclock and the thermometer in the shade was 80 degrees in the afternoon there was a very light air of wind S.E. and the Thermometer 90 Went to a Religious Meeting in the evening by Rvd Richard Mitchell
The wind Southerly Thermometer 78 degr Hauled up freight in morning and turned croquet mallets Worked apart of the afternoon on flying jibboom for black warrior recd letter from  G.W. Bagley
The wind South West Thermometer 85 degrees high in the shade wrote letters to G.W. Bagley and Frank Woodard

The wind Southerly & foggy most all day & the Thermometer 78 degrees made cushion for waggon seat and work about the house getting ready for summer boarders Went Mrs. Dr E.J. Frenchs Lecture on Manakin or keep good health.
The wind Easterly in morning then Southerly Thermometer 81 degrees. No Celebration at this place except fireing Canon and going on Pic Nic In the evening fireworks and a dance at my house.
The wind North West. Thermometer 80 degrees in the shade as it is on the North side of the House.
The wind North West Thermometer 70 degrees Went to Bar Harbor with R Pendleton Came back in Warren Smiths skiff My cook came on the Lewiston to Bar Harbor Came over with R Pendleton
The wind Southerly Thermometer 70 degrees Went on Isen Bound + Jordans Island
The wind Southerly Thermometer 76Â° Wrote letters to S.C. Forsaith & Co. Walter Wood S.L. Dennison owners of Str Magnet Genl Agt of Sto Chas Houghton A.J.Chapman Esq.
NA
NA
NA
NA
NA
NA

The wind Northerly Thermometer 52 Wrote letter to owners of Steamer Magnet Drove stage from Winter Harbor to W. Gouldsboro Recd letters from S.C. Forsaith & Co. & A White of Hingham Hired Mrs J.D. Fernald for cook for the summer
The wind Southerly Thermometer 62 degrees Wrote letter to A White of Hingham work buiilding steps to flat form and clearing up door yard.
The wind Southerly and rainy all day fresh breeze in afternoon Thermometer 55 degrees Cut door throng from dining room to store room.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 70 degrees work abt the house putting shelves in store room &e Recd card from G.L. Dennison
The wind Northerly in forenoon Went to Bar Harbor to Telegraph. The wind very moderate Southerly Started for home at 7p.m.
The wind Easterly Thermometer 68 degrees Wrote letter to Elias Hale & CC Vedall. Recd Letter from Elias J Hale

The wind Southerly Thermometer 62 Went on a ride to the sands and to the Marsh accompanied by my wife and child Went to a religious meeting in the evening advertised in the Boston Daily Evening Traveler $1878 to be paid in year
The wind Southerly Thermometer 62 degrees helped J.F. Kingsley in the afternoon get his hay. Bought one half ton of hay and put it in T.R. Hammonds barn
The wind Northerly Thermometer 68Â° in the forenoon and overcast in the afternoon clear weather Thermometer 72Â° help J Kingsley all day haying.
The wind North West. Thermometer 74 degrees Work for J.F. Kingsley haying. hauled in five loads
The wind Southerly Thermometer 72 degrees work for J.F. Kingsley hauled in two loads of hay.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 58 moderate rain in the afternoon. Hauled one load of hay in barn in forenoon for J.F.K

The wind S.S. East in forenoon and very heavy rain In the afternoon cleared up Thermometer 70Â° degrees wrote letters to Geo S Peters and A White of Hingham work apart of the day on Express wagon for my self turning hub &e
The wind North West Thermometer 72 degrees Help J.F. Kingsley haul in 4 loads of hay. had party from Bar Harbor to stay over night
The wind Southerly helped J.F. Kingsley on his hay finished mowing Company left for Bar Harbor Recd letter from Boston Post Went to W Gouldsboro at night and got some ice.
The wind moderate Southerly and overcast. Thermometer 58 degrees Hauled in load of hay and left it on the rack
The wind Easterly and overcast Thermometer 65 Work on exclusion in the Steamer Everett accompanied by wife & child to Sullivan + Bar Harbor
The wind Southerly Thermometer wrote letters to G.S. Peters M Gallery &Co & Eldridge & Perry. Recd letter from Mary Smallidge
The wind Easterly and rainy all day The Thermometer 56Â° Work apart of the day Kneeing abt boat Went to West Gouldsboro at night to Carry Mrs Eunice Kingsley
The wind Southerly Thermometer 58 degrees Wrote letter to Mary Smallidge. finished the boat that was begun last winter Recd letter from M. Gallant &Co.
The wind Moderate South East and apart of the day foggy. Thermometer 56 Went to a religious meeting in the evening Took boat of for the first time that I finished yesterday
The wind South East Thermometer 58 1/2 degrees Wrote letter to Mr Vose Recieved Mrs Lizzie Amisden the first summer boarder for the season
The wind South East Thermometer 58 degrees fogg most all day. Went to Iron Bernd in my new boat
The wind South East. Thermometer 61Â° racing in morning and again at night heavy showers Went to Lizzie May Ulmers Theatre at Winter Harbor.
The wind West North West in forenoon & clear Thermometer 68 West to Prospect Harbor with horse work about home most the day Wrote letter to Louis Oshurn & Co.
The wind Southerly and overcast a little showery Thermometer 65 Went to Bar Harbor in Kay Waynard after freight and boots.
The wind Westerly Thermometer 67 1/2 degrees Made axletree stock for my wagon
The wind North West in forenoon and S.W. in afternoon Thermometer 72Â°
The wind Northerly in the morning Went to Bar Harbor in Kate Waynard to see abt a party comming over Thermometer 71 degrees Left Bar Harbor at 4:30 pm for home arrived at 6:30
The wind Southerly Thermometer 68 degrees put down carpet in forenoon And in the afternoon went to Bar Harbor after Mr Stevenson belonging to U.S. Survey boat
The wind very moderate Southerly and Easterly and thick with fog. Thermometer 79 degrees Went to Prospect with horse to Cary Mr & Mrs Amsdan & Mr Stevenson. Recd Telegraph dispatch from Wm Pendleton.
Calm and foggy all day Thermometer 74 degrees Made over a pair of oars for myself MessrsLouis Oshurn & Co. Put down carpet.
The wind South Easterly And thick with fog. Thermometer 69 degrees work apart of the day fixing up stable. Recd letter from the Capt of the U.S. Steamer Gedna
column34: Looks pretty accurate but he might be refering to USC&GS Thomas R. Gedney

column3: The wind Southerly and in the fore noon rainy afternoon foggy Thermometer 69 degrees Went to Bar Harbor in my boat to Cary the mail for the US Steamer Gedna
The wind South Easterly Thermometer 62 degrees rainy most all day heavy with thunder and very sharp lightning
column25: rainy, heavy with thunder and very sharp lightning
column26: rainy, heavy with thunder and very sharp lightning
column27: rainy, heavy with thunder and very sharp lightning

column3: The wind North West and pleasant most of the day until abt 2 pm when there came up a very heavy shower Work all day making main boom for A.G. Brooks Recd a letter from M. Gallant Thermometer 69 degrees
The wind North West Thermometer 72 degrees work all day on boom for A.G. Brooks Mrs Garvin came to board
The wind Northerly Thermometer 70 degrees work abt home.
The wind Northerly then Easterly and pleasant Thermometer 65 work abt home. Wrote letter home Mr. Wm B Viall of Bethel V.T.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 68Â°  tending out about home with boarders
The wind Southerly fresh breeze. Thermometer 59Â° fixed rudder to my new boat and worked abt home Recd letter from Ascan Handy
The wind Southerly Thermometer 60 degrees heavy rain all day at night cleaned up went out Mrs. E.J. French religious meeting in the evening
The wind Southerly Thermometer 57 degrees put pump in sail boat. repaired buggy and work about the house
The wind moderate all day Thermometer 70 had 11 people in one party from the Rodick House to dinner.
moderate southerly wind Thermometer 68 degrees high Took new boat and went of in the sound to Porgie Steamer and saw the Seine 300 Bbls porgies at one haul
column4: The Sound (Frenchman Bay or Winter Harbor Sound)

column3: The wind Southerly in the afternoon foggy Thermometer 62 degrees Acknowledged deed for Wm Rand & Elesher Bickford. Had horse showed made grain box had party of 6 from Sullivan to Supper Mrs Amesden & Mrs Garoin left for Prospect
The wind very moderate Southerly Thermometer 82 Went to Ellsworth accompanied by any wife to see Creditors and other buisness came home at night
The wind Southerly Thermometer 64 degrees hauled up new boat discharged the cook Recd letters from Hale & Emery. Boston Evening Traveller and Lovell Courier.
The wind South East Heavy rain all day. Thermometer 60 degrees
Calm all day and overcast Thermometer 75 degrees Commenced work for Wm Guptill finishing the inside of his house Work all day. At night went to Indian Harbor to Carry Rebecca & Emma Cranby
The wind Easterly Thermometer 68 degrees Work for Wm Guptill on house Recd notice from Wm B Viall he had accepted my offer to carry the mail
The wind Easterly Thermometer 65 degrees work abt home. mended Harness &c

The wind Easterly and moderate overcast and apart of the day foggy. Thermometer 65Â° Sent the contract to Wm B Viall taking upon my self the responsibility as mail carrier. Went to Bar Harbor to carry Capt David Move back in afternoon.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 70 degrees work in forenoon lathing in house for Wm Guptill at night heavy shower
The wind Easterly & clear Thermometer 64Â° Work all day for Mr Wm Guptill on house Wrote letter to Messrs J.W. Davis & son.
column34: Realized that Mysrs might be Messrs

column3: The wind Southerly Thermometer 60 degrees. Went to Mrs. Dr E J Frenchs religious meeting in the evening.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 59Â° degrees. Went to State Election
The wind Southerly Thermometer 63 degrees Went up to the Marsh with my wife black-berrying back at night.
The wind Easterly and overcast Thermometer 58 work all day for Wm Guptill on house Went to Mrs. E J Frenchs lecture on health in evening.
The wind Easterly foggy and rainy all day Thermometer 60Â° Work all day for Wm Guptill on his house Recd letter from Wm B Viall Bethel  V.T. Wrote letter to Messrs J.W. Davis & son
The wind South East Fresh breeze and heavy storm Thermometer 65 Work all day for Wm Guptill on house.
The wind South West Cleared of blowing very heavy Thermometer 64 work all day for Wm Guptill Made oath as Mail Carrier before H D Coombs
The wind Westerly. Thermometer 65Â° Went to West Gouldsboro and back. wrote letter to Mary Smallidge Mt Desert
The wind very moderate Southerly Thermometer 65 Work all day for William Guptill on his house lathing.
The wind Southerly and the Thermometer 48 degrees high in the morning frost Recd Postal Card from H B Saunders Ellsworth Work all day fom Wm Guptill on house.
The wind Southerly & foggy Thermometer 65 degrees Work all day for Wm Guptill on house finish lathing over Head
The wind Southerly Thermometer 61 degrees Wrote letter to American Office. Work all day for Wm Guptill.
The wind Southerly and thick with fog all day Thermometer 60 work about home. Wrote letter to Saml Libby

The wind Southerly and very thick with fog Thermometer 60 degrees helped Wm Guptill clear chips out of his house in forenoon. And in the afternoon went to Prospect to Carry Mr Garain. Recd letter from American Office & G W Davis at night showers
The wind North West and pleasant Thermometer 64 went to the Baptism of Alonzo Sumner & Mrs. I. B. Foss at the Sand Beach in Winter Harbor Went to the Lords Supper after the Baptism
column34: Is pleasant a weather condition or a wind speed?

column3: The wind Westerly and the Thermometer 54 degrees Went to the ferry after a new two seated express waggon bought of JW Davis Ellsworth. back at night
The wind South West. Thermometer 59 degrees. Recd letter from Wm B Viall Went to Prospect to cary P A Sumner
The wind Westerly Thermometer 60 degrees Wrote letter to Messrs SC Muney & Co.
The wind South very fresh breeze and foggy Thermometer 59 degrees Wrote letters to NH Higgins & Wm B Viall Went to a Religious meeting in the evening very heavy rain at 9 pm
The wind North West Thermometer 58 degrees Painted boats bottom and got ready to go gunning tomorrow

The wind West North West Thermometer in morning 50 Went gunning With Martin Pendleton at Schoodic Island We got 6 birds home in afternoon. Recd letters from American Office and Second Post Master General.
The wind Southerly Went to Milbridge to Carry two men belonging to the US Steamer Gedney of the Coast Survey back at night the Thermometer 51 degrees
The wind Southerly Thermometer 63 degrees

The wind South West and foggy in forenoon Thermometer 60 degrees Went as one of the surveyors on the Schr Elizabeth at Tracys Dock at Winter Harbor and condemed her. dug my potatoes Recd Postal Card from Wm Viall
column34: Tracys Dock may be a locatable location

column3: The wind South West Thermometer 58 degrees high weather foggy. Went down gunning in forenoon and in the afternoon went to Sullivan to see Stephen Kingley.
Very moderate all day with an air of wind all around the compass The Thermometer 73 above bought one ton of hay of J.T. Kingsley and hauled it home. Helped Colen Pendleton on his dora to make tight

The wind North West Thermometer 61 degrees Administered the oath to G.W. Tracy quarterly returns of Post office. Commenced driving mail for the first time on the new route by the way of Hammonds Corner
The wind North West and the Thermometer 55Â° Work about home waiting upon the traveling public maile jack to lift waggon Went to West Gouldsboro in afternoon.
The wind Northerly Thermometer 54 degrees
The wind North West in forenoon and S. West in afternoon Thermometer 63 Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail
The wind Southerly and overcast. Started to go a gunning commenced raining gave it up. In the afternoon the wind West South West Thermometer 52 degrees
The wind Southerly and very fresh breeze and overcast. Thermometer 59 at 8 PM heavy rain with thunder & lightning
The wind North West & Fresh Gale Thermometer 45
The wind from North East to South South East. and the Thermometer 40Â° Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail.
The wind Easterly & overcast. Thermometer 45 drove the Mail to West Gouldsboro by the way of Prospect for David Weare.
column4: Prospect Harbor, West Gouldsboro, Winter Harbor

column3: The wind North fresh gale Thermometer 42.
The wind South West Thermometer 45 degrees Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail. worked one fourth day for G.W. Tracy moving partiitions.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 55 degrees Work one half day for G.W. Tracy fixing the partitions. Recd letter from Boston Daily Traveler
The wind Southerly and very moderate Thermometer 58 degrees Work apart of the day for Melvin Torrey Casing out door &c.
The wind Southerly and foggy. Thermometer 52 Work in the forenoon for Melvin Torrey hanging and in after noon work for Wm Guptill on house
The wind Southerly Thermometer 52 degrees weather foggy at dark heavy rain. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail.
